Machine learning and Algorithmic Bias

"Machine learning is the scientific study of algorithms and statistical models that computer systems use to perform a specific task without using explicit instructions, relying on patterns and inference instead." (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Machine_learning)

In essence, machine learning is a way to teach a computer system to attempt to learn on its own. Although it offers many positives, there are some downsides to machine learning. In particular, the human element, along with all of its flaws, bleeding into these systems are responsible for some of these downsides. One way to describe a flaw like this is called algorithmic bias. "Algorithmic bias describes systematic and repeatable errors in a computer system that create unfair outcomes, such as privileging one arbitrary group of users over others"(https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algorithmic_bias).

There are several types of algorithmic bias, including pre-existing, technical, and emergent. For this project, we will be focusing on emergent biases that arise in machine learning systems. "Emergent bias is the result of the use and reliance on algorithms across new or unanticipated contexts. Algorithms may not have been adjusted to consider new forms of knowledge, such as new drugs or medical breakthroughs, new laws, business models, or shifting cultural norms"(https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algorithmic_bias).

We will attempt to display this emergent bias with models we build on different pitches thrown in Major League Baseball seasons, and observing the ways they behave when tested.

On attempting to create emergent bias

Throughout this lesson, it is important to keep in mind the following definition we are trying to display:

Emergent bias being the result of the use and reliance on algorithms across new or unanticipated contents. Algorithms may not have been adjusted to consider new forms of knowledge, such as new drugs or medical breakthroughs, new laws, business models, or shifting cultural norms.

We choose to attempt to demonstrate emergent bias through the use of baseball pitches throughout eras. It is easy to hypothesize that throughout time, the game of baseball, as with all things, evolves. Pitching styles and other factors may contribute to completely different tactics and behaviors compared to different eras. The main idea behind our strategy in displaying an emergent bias is as follows: 1) Train two models on particular baseball seasons' pitches 2) Attempt to predict, with these models, the pitches thrown for specific game scenarios in other seasons 3) Compare the two model's success rates in picking 'successful' pitches, where a successful pitch is defined as a pitch that does not result in any advantageous outcome for the opposing team.

It is important to note that what we choose to quantify in describing our characteristics, as well as what season's and methods we choose, are purely subjective. The main thing we are trying to do is attempt to display if emergent biases result.

Again, we are attempting to display the following:

Emergent bias being the result of the use and reliance on algorithms across new or unanticipated contents. Algorithms may not have been adjusted to consider new forms of knowledge, such as new drugs or medical breakthroughs, new laws, business models, or shifting cultural norms.

Where the models we create for specific seasons are put into scenarios where new or unanticipated contents may arise, such as testing a 2008 season model with a different era, such as a 2019 season.

Part 1: Training our models

In order to highlight emergent bias, it is important to understand some of the concepts of machine learning.

Machine Learning

Machine learning problems fall into a few categories, namely deciding between supervised learning and unsupervised learning.

Supervised Learning

With supervised learning, data comes with additional attributes that we would like to predict. We can again split this problem into two different problems: 1) Classification. This is the scenario where we have two or more classes, and would like to learn from already labeled data to predict the class of unlabeled data. An example would be trying to classify unknown data into 1 of 10 possible digits. 2) Regression. This is the scenario when we would like to predict attributes about data, but the variables are continuous. An example would be trying to predict the weight of a child given age and height.

The biggest difference between problems in supervised learning is whether or not the outcome of what we're trying to predict is continuous or discrete. If we are trying classify, we know that the potential variables are discrete. If we are performing regression, then the potential variables can be anything(continuous).

Unsupervised Learning

The goal with unsupervised learning is trying to learn from data without any target values to assign/learn from. Examples of these kinds of problems include clustering, density estimation, or visualization of data.

Resources for learning more about these concepts can be found here:

  • https://scikit-learn.org/stable/tutorial/basic/tutorial.html
  • https://scikit-learn.org/stable/
Applying it to our problem

For our purposes, we will largely rely on classification of our data. We aim to use attributes of data (pitch count, date of game, balls/strikes count, outcome of at-bat) to assign to discrete variables(types of pitch thrown in those scenarios). In particular, we will only be training our models with successful pitches. In doing so, we hope to teach our models by giving them data which has lead to success. We could similarly teach our models what not to do, and make our decisions and predictions based on that, but doing it in this way leads to more concrete analysis techniques. The first task is as follows:

1) Train two models on particular baseball seasons' pitches

We can break this up into several different steps: 1) Gather our data 2) Format our data for our classifiers 3) Train our classifiers

Step 2: Formatting our data for our classifiers

As of now, we have the data for the appropriate data we want to train from, and the data we want to test with.

As well, we've observed the characteristics we would like our data to be described with.

Additionally, we have determined the events and descriptions by which our data can be separated into.

Now, our goal is to train a dataset from pitches we deem successful. The idea is to train a model to throw good pitches, avoiding to learn anything about a bad pitch. A 'successful' can be defined as one that does not result in an advantageous result for the batter. In a purely subjective manner, we choose pitches that avoid any of the following:

  • In columns 'description':

    • hit_into_play_no_out
    • hit_into_play_score

  • In columns 'events':

    • single
    • walk
    • double
    • hit_by_pitch
    • triple
    • home_run
    • intent_walk
    • sac_fly

In avoiding these scenarios, any pitch we throw would have resulted in an outcome not favorable to our batter.

We define our data's characteristics to contain the following information:

  • 17 stand
  • 18 p_throws
  • 24 balls
  • 25 strikes
  • 34 outs_when_up
  • 35 inning
  • 36 inning_topbot
  • 76 at_bat_number
  • 77 pitch_number
  • 79 home_score
  • 80 away_score
  • 81 bat_score

Again, in a purely subjective manner, we hope this encompasses a game scenario as best as it can for a baseball game.

Our first order of business will be to filter the appropriate training data sets into the characteristics we desire. We will filter out the undesirable events to get only 'successful' pitches, and from that set, we will grab our training data with appropriate characteristics, as well as our truth data.

In [6]:
# The goal of this function will be to separate the panda dataframe containing our csv file information into a format by which we can apply our machine learning functions. It will grab the relevant data by which we wish to describe our data, and the corresponding truths data for training.

# input a panda of data, return a list of [training data,truths]
def transform_data(data_panda):
    
    # we get a dataframe of relevant event outcomes we wish to avoid. This can be modified to make our data more or less specific
    # in this model, we choose to avoid outcomes advantageous to the batter
    data_panda_filtered = data_panda[(data_panda.events != 'walk') & (data_panda.events != 'single') & (data_panda.events != 'double') & (data_panda.events != 'hit_by_pitch') & (data_panda.events != 'single') & (data_panda.events != 'single') & (data_panda.events != 'single') & (data_panda.events != 'triple') & (data_panda.events != 'home_run') & (data_panda.events != 'intent_walk') & (data_panda.events != 'sac_fly') & (data_panda.events != 'run') & (data_panda.pitch_type != np.nan) ]

    # we get the characteristics by which we describe our data from the filtered dataframe above
    # This is where we can add or subtract attributes should we wish to change the way we describe our data
    # the relevant_id[] list is the same list declared earlier, which we use to index into columns without needing to type the specific strings
    data_panda_data = data_panda_filtered[[relevant_id[17],relevant_id[18],relevant_id[24],relevant_id[25],relevant_id[34],relevant_id[35],relevant_id[36],relevant_id[76],relevant_id[77],relevant_id[79],relevant_id[80],relevant_id[81]]]
    
    # We convert strings to numericals, since our classifier function requires this
    # If we change which columns we describe our data, we will need to change the strings in that column into numericals as well.
    data_panda_data = data_panda_data.replace('Top', 0.0, regex=True)
    data_panda_data = data_panda_data.replace('Bot', 1.0, regex=True)
    data_panda_data = data_panda_data.replace('L', 0.0, regex=True)
    data_panda_data = data_panda_data.replace('R', 1.0, regex=True)
    data_panda_data = data_panda_data.replace(np.nan, 0.0, regex=True)
    data_panda_data = data_panda_data.to_numpy() # Converting our data dataframe into an ndarray
    
    # The classifier function requires our data to be an ndarray
    
    # Grabbing our ground truths
    data_panda_truth = data_panda_filtered.pitch_type
    # Converting pitches in string form to numericals
    # It is important to take note of these string to numerical changes, as we will use these numericals for analysis down the line
    data_panda_truth = data_panda_truth.replace(np.nan, 0.0, regex=True)
    data_panda_truth = data_panda_truth.replace('SI', 1.0, regex=True)
    data_panda_truth = data_panda_truth.replace('FF', 2.0, regex=True)
    data_panda_truth = data_panda_truth.replace('CU', 3.0, regex=True)
    data_panda_truth = data_panda_truth.replace('SL', 4.0, regex=True)
    data_panda_truth = data_panda_truth.replace('CH', 5.0, regex=True)
    data_panda_truth = data_panda_truth.replace('EP', 6.0, regex=True)
    data_panda_truth = data_panda_truth.replace('FS', 7.0, regex=True)
    data_panda_truth = data_panda_truth.replace('IN', 8.0, regex=True)
    data_panda_truth = data_panda_truth.replace('FC', 9.0, regex=True)
    data_panda_truth = data_panda_truth.replace('FT', 10.0, regex=True)
    data_panda_truth = data_panda_truth.replace('KN', 11.0, regex=True)
    data_panda_truth = data_panda_truth.replace('PO', 12.0, regex=True)
    data_panda_truth = data_panda_truth.replace('KC', 13.0, regex=True)
    data_panda_truth = data_panda_truth.replace('FA', 14.0, regex=True)
    data_panda_truth = data_panda_truth.replace('UN', 15.0, regex=True)
    data_panda_truth = data_panda_truth.to_numpy() # converting to array for clf
    
    #https://stackoverflow.com/questions/45346550/valueerror-unknown-label-type-unknown
    data_panda_truth = data_panda_truth.astype('int') # converting to ints for our classifying function as well
    
    return [data_panda_data, data_panda_truth]

It is important to take note of the numerical values we assign to the string of pitch_types we transform from.

In our case, we declared them as follows:

  • np.nan = 0
  • SI = 1
  • FF = 2
  • CU = 3
  • SL = 4
  • CH = 5
  • EP = 6
  • FS = 7
  • IN = 8
  • FC = 9
  • FT = 10
  • KN = 11
  • PO = 12
  • KC = 13
  • FA = 14
  • UN = 15

The specifics of what each pitch type is, such as FF being four-seam fastball, is not important for those unfamiliar with baseball. We are mostly concerned with the trends related to pitch selection.

Part 2: Predicting

As a reminder, we are trying to determine if an emergent bias will result from our models being applied to new contexts.

We have accomplished the following so far: 1) Train two models on particular baseball seasons' pitches

We move on to the next tasks:

2) Attempt to predict, with these models, the pitches thrown for specific game scenarios in other seasons

3) Compare the two model's success rates in picking 'successful' pitches, where a successful pitch is defined as a pitch that does not result in any advantageous outcome for the opposing team.

In [18]:
# input parameters are our learned models, and a data set resulting from the transform_data()
def test_seasons(clf1,clf2,test_set):
    
    # predict using given models on already formatted data
    model_one_predictions = clf1.predict(test_set[0][:])
    model_two_predictions = clf2.predict(test_set[0][:])
    
    # Observing what pitches our model chose, and counting how many of them there were
    dict1 = {}
    for x in model_one_predictions:
        if x not in dict1:
            dict1[x] = 1
        else:
            dict1[x] += 1
    dict2 = {}
    for x in model_two_predictions:
        if x not in dict2:
            dict2[x] = 1
        else:
            dict2[x] += 1
    print("clf1 pitch_type predictions:",dict1)
    print("clf2 pitch_type predictions:",dict2)
    
    # Determining how many 'successful' pitches were chosen
    counter = 0
    model_one_success = 0
    for x in test_set[1][:]:
        if x == model_one_predictions[counter]:
            model_one_success+=1
        counter+=1
    counter = 0
    model_two_success = 0
    for x in test_set[1][:]:
        if x == model_two_predictions[counter]:
            model_two_success+=1
        counter+=1
    print("clf1 prediction success rate:", model_one_success*1.0 / (len(test_set[1])))
    print("clf2 prediction success rate:", model_two_success*1.0 / (len(test_set[1])))

Part 3: Analysis

We will be analyzing the data we've accumulated and addressing our next task:

3) Compare the two model's success rates in picking 'successful' pitches, where a successful pitch is defined as a pitch that does not result in any advantageous outcome for the opposing team.

In the previous section, we tested a model trained on Clayton Kershaw's 2008 season successful pitches. As well, we tested a model trained on Clayton Kershaw's 2018 season successful pitches. Both of these models were tested on Clayton Kershaw's 2019 season. The data is as follows:

clf1 pitch_type predictions: {2: 2454, 0: 29}

clf2 pitch_type predictions: {4: 1521, 2: 962}

clf1 prediction success rate: 0.424083769633508

clf2 prediction success rate: 0.490132903745469

clf1 corresponds to the model trained on Kershaw's 2008 season, while cf2 corresponds to the model trained on Kershaw's 2018 season.

clf1 exclusively chose to pitch with four-seam fastball(2).

clf2 would choose between a mix of four-seam fastballs(2) and sliders(4).

An observation we can make:

  • Our second model performed better than our first model.

Intuitively, this makes sense. 2018 Kershaw is in the same baseball era as 2019 Kershaw, and a lot of the characteristics in 2019 Kershaw are derived from 2018 Kershaw. 2008 Kershaw performed less successfully at choosing a 'successful' pitch, but not by a drastic amount. This could be due to the fact that 2008 Kershaw's four-seam fastball is definitively great, and this is historically true as well.

Let us perform the same analysis of our models on a different season, specifically 2009. We hope to see the same behavior, in that our 2008 Kershaw performs better than our 2018 Kershaw.

Now, we see a staggering difference. 2008 Kershaw performed nearly twice as well as 2018 Kershaw, when testing on Kershaw's 2009 season. This is clearly more evident of an emergent bias. We've taken our 2018 Kershaw model and subjected him to unforeseen circumstances, and its decreased performance can be seen.

To be a bit more thorough and a bit less biased, we can test our 2008 and 2018 models against other pitchers as a whole.

We are observing that our 2018 model of Clayton Kershaw does not do as well testing in earlier seasons than he does in later seasons. Our 2008 model performs noticeably better than the 2018 season when testing on Kershaw's 2009 season, and nearly as well as our 2018 model in Kershaw's 2019 season. One way we can reason this is a transformation in Kershaw's repertoire. Anecdotally, Clayton Kershaw's best pitch in 2008 was his fastball. 2018 saw a reduction in his fastball usage, mainly due to a lack of velocity and lowered success with it due to injuries. 2018 also saw a rise in his use of the slider pitch, as modeled by what our models learned. It stands to reason that Kershaw's transformation and success can be attributed to developing an effective secondary pitch once his dominating fastball began to degrade in effectiveness. This could explain how his 2008 pitch repertoire and selection is still an effective pitch in a different era, as opposed to his less effective 2018 pitch repertoire performing in a different era.

Comparing our Kershaw models to Dodgers pitching staff models resulted in something a little less evident of any emergent bias. These comparisons are not entirely fair to our models, and say little about them, since they are specifically trained to be tested on Kershaw's own repertoire. The models will naturally not be able to predict pitches they've never seen before, such as a knuckleball or cutter. We merely see that the 2008 Kershaw model is a more robust model than 2018 Kershaw, since the 2008 Kershaw model is reliant on the four-seam fastball. We can try to reason this as follows.

We can observe the most dominant pitches in baseball by viewing what pitches got outs.

In order to do this, we attempt to split pitches into all pitches that resulted in an out. From every possible event, we want to avoid these events which do not result in an out:

  • single
  • walk
  • hit_by_pitch
  • field_error
  • double
  • sac_fly
  • sac_bunt
  • fielders_choice
  • triple
  • home_run

Our goal in doing so is to attempt to find the most used pitches to get a batter out in each count.

In [23]:
# We define a function to format our data to filter pitches that results in an out
def format_out_pitches(season):
    season_mod = season[(season.events != 'single') & (season.events != 'walk') & (season.events != 'hit_by_pitch') & (season.events != 'field_error') & (season.events != 'double') & (season.events != 'sac_fly') & (season.events != 'sac_bunt') & (season.events != 'fielders_choice') & (season.events != 'triple') & (season.events != 'home_run') & (season.pitch_type != np.nan) & (season.events != 'intent_walk') & (season.pitch_type != 'IN') & (season.pitch_type != 'NaN')]
    return season_mod

# get list of counts [0-0,0-1,0-2,1-0,1-1,1-2...3-2] of out pitches
def filter_out_counts(out_pitches):
    pitches = format_out_pitches(out_pitches)
    
    # We only care about our dataframe's pitch_type, balls, and strikes attributes
    pitches_filtered = pitches[[relevant_id[0],relevant_id[24],relevant_id[25]]]
    count00 = pitches_filtered[(pitches_filtered.balls == 0) & (pitches_filtered.strikes == 0)]
    count01 = pitches_filtered[(pitches_filtered.balls == 0) & (pitches_filtered.strikes == 1)]
    count02 = pitches_filtered[(pitches_filtered.balls == 0) & (pitches_filtered.strikes == 2)]
    count10 = pitches_filtered[(pitches_filtered.balls == 1) & (pitches_filtered.strikes == 0)]
    count11 = pitches_filtered[(pitches_filtered.balls == 1) & (pitches_filtered.strikes == 1)]
    count12 = pitches_filtered[(pitches_filtered.balls == 1) & (pitches_filtered.strikes == 2)]
    count20 = pitches_filtered[(pitches_filtered.balls == 2) & (pitches_filtered.strikes == 0)]
    count21 = pitches_filtered[(pitches_filtered.balls == 2) & (pitches_filtered.strikes == 1)]
    count22 = pitches_filtered[(pitches_filtered.balls == 2) & (pitches_filtered.strikes == 2)]
    count30 = pitches_filtered[(pitches_filtered.balls == 3) & (pitches_filtered.strikes == 0)]
    count31 = pitches_filtered[(pitches_filtered.balls == 3) & (pitches_filtered.strikes == 1)]
    count32 = pitches_filtered[(pitches_filtered.balls == 3) & (pitches_filtered.strikes == 2)]
    return [count00,count01,count02,count10,count11,count12,count20,count21,count22,count30,count31,count32]
    
    
# getting each pitch thrown for every count
def count_pitches(count):
    pitch_dict = {}
    for x in count['pitch_type']:
        if x is np.nan:
            continue
        if x not in pitch_dict:
            pitch_dict[x] = 1
        else:
            pitch_dict[x] += 1
    return pitch_dict

#https://www.tutorialspoint.com/numpy/numpy_matplotlib.htm
def graph_pitches(count_dict, title):
    list_x = []
    list_y = []
    
    # getting pitch counts for each pitch
    for x in count_dict:
        list_x.append(x)
        list_y.append(count_dict[x])

    plt.bar(list_x, list_y, align = 'center') 
    plt.title(title) 
    plt.ylabel('Number of Pitches') 
    plt.xlabel('Type of Pitch') 
    plt.show()

    # calling all of the previous functions to graph every possible pitch's ball/strike count that resulted in outs for a given season
def graph_pitches_master(season):
    [count00,count01,count02,count10,count11,count12,count20,count21,count22,count30,count31,count32] = filter_out_counts(season)
    count00_pitches = count_pitches(count00)
    count01_pitches = count_pitches(count01)
    count02_pitches = count_pitches(count02)
    count10_pitches = count_pitches(count10)
    count11_pitches = count_pitches(count11)
    count12_pitches = count_pitches(count12)
    count20_pitches = count_pitches(count20)
    count21_pitches = count_pitches(count21)
    count22_pitches = count_pitches(count22)
    count30_pitches = count_pitches(count30)
    count31_pitches = count_pitches(count31)
    count32_pitches = count_pitches(count32)
    graph_pitches(count00_pitches,'0-0 Count Pitches')
    graph_pitches(count01_pitches,'0-1 Count Pitches')
    graph_pitches(count02_pitches,'0-2 Count Pitches')
    graph_pitches(count10_pitches,'1-0 Count Pitches')
    graph_pitches(count11_pitches,'1-1 Count Pitches')
    graph_pitches(count12_pitches,'1-2 Count Pitches')
    graph_pitches(count20_pitches,'2-0 Count Pitches')
    graph_pitches(count21_pitches,'2-1 Count Pitches')
    graph_pitches(count22_pitches,'2-2 Count Pitches')
    graph_pitches(count30_pitches,'3-0 Count Pitches')
    graph_pitches(count31_pitches,'3-1 Count Pitches')
    graph_pitches(count32_pitches,'3-2 Count Pitches')

As we can observe from 2018 Kershaw, the slider pitch became more dominant and used for getting outs. Again, this makes sense as to why he would perform more poorly against a more general 2019 Dodgers pitching staff. These behaviors are more of a result of our models not being able to be fully described with the data we're given (such as clutchness, age, wear due to injury, social pressures, or anxieties). These have very little to do with the topic of algorithmic bias, but help in explaining why our models behave the way they do. If we were to observe the graphs from above applied to Kershaw's 2009 and 2019 season, or the Dodgers' 2009 season, we would see why 2008 Kershaw can continue to be competitive (he was able to rely on his fastball), and why 2018 Kershaw isnt (he has to rely on his slider more, which is not as effective in getting outs in earlier seasons).

Conclusions

In this presentation, we were able to display emergent biases that arose in machine learning applications. We did this by training models on a baseball player's pitch performances across different eras. In particular, we showed an emergent bias that arose when testing our 2018 baseball player's season model's ability to predict successful pitches of that baseball player's 2009 season. He performed noticeably worse, as a result of our models being asked to perform predictions across new and unanticipated contexts(in our case, asking our model to perform in a fastball dominated situation with a model that relies on a mix of sliders and fastballs).

Our model trained on Kershaw's 2010 season performed better at predicting 2011 successful pitches than our model trained on Kershaw's 2017 season. Although the difference may be slight, it is there. Based on every out pitch recorded at every count, these results make sense. Our testing model, Kershaw's 2011 season, saw an increase in the usage of his slider pitch compared to his earlier seasons, but he still primarily used his fastball to get players out. Kershaw's 2010 season saw a less dramatic increase in his usage of the slider compared to 2011's increase, but his fastball was, again, the primary pitch used to get players out. 2017 Kershaw sees a dramatic rise in usage of his slider to get players out as compared to these 2011,2010 seasons. 2011's large mix of sliders and fastballs contributes to both of the 2010 and 2017 models performing fairly well, but the dominance of Kershaw's 2010 fastball edging out 2017's higher slider usage makes sense. A case for an emergent bias being observed here can be made.
